.TH READSEEK 1 "2026-06-14" "readseek 0.2.2" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
readseek \- structural source reader with stable line hashes
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
\fBreadseek\fR [\fB\-h\fR|\fB--help\fR]
\fBreadseek\fR [\fB\-V\fR|\fB--version\fR]

\fBreadseek file\fR [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    (\fB--stdin --path\fR \fIpath\fR | \fItarget\fR)

\fBreadseek read\fR [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    [\fB--start\fR \fIline\fR|\fB--offset\fR \fIline\fR]
    [\fB--end\fR \fIline\fR|\fB--limit\fR \fIn\fR]
    (\fB--stdin --path\fR \fIpath\fR | \fItarget\fR)

\fBreadseek map\fR [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    (\fB--stdin --path\fR \fIpath\fR | \fItarget\fR)

\fBreadseek symbol\fR [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR] [\fB--line\fR \fIline\fR]
    (\fB--stdin --path\fR \fIpath\fR [\fIqualified-name\fR] | \fItarget\fR [\fIqualified-name\fR])

\fBreadseek identify\fR [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    [\fB--line\fR \fIline\fR] [\fB--column\fR \fIcolumn\fR]
    (\fB--stdin --path\fR \fIpath\fR | \fItarget\fR)

\fBreadseek definition\fR [\fB--stdin\fR] [\fB--compact\fR] [\fB\-c\fR|\fB--cached\fR] [\fB\-o\fR|\fB--others\fR]
    [\fB\-i\fR|\fB--ignored\fR] [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    \fItarget\fR [\fIname\fR]

\fBreadseek references\fR [\fB--compact\fR] [\fB\-c\fR|\fB--cached\fR] [\fB\-o\fR|\fB--others\fR]
    [\fB\-i\fR|\fB--ignored\fR] [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    \fItarget\fR \fIname\fR

\fBreadseek search\fR [\fB\-c\fR|\fB--cached\fR] [\fB\-o\fR|\fB--others\fR]
    [\fB\-i\fR|\fB--ignored\fR] [\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR]
    \fItarget\fR \fIpattern\fR
.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B readseek
reads source files and emits pretty-printed JSON for tools that need stable,
line-addressable source context. It can detect file languages, return hashed
line ranges, build structural source maps, read symbols, identify cursor
context, find definitions and references, and run AST pattern searches.
.PP
Source-bearing output uses
.I hashlines:
a one-based line number, a 3-character line hash, and the original line text.
Line hashes are short stable references that can be used as target suffixes in
later calls.
.PP
.B readseek
is intended for scripts, editors, and coding agents. Human-facing diagnostics
are written separately from JSON output.
.PP
.B definition
and
.B references
support
.B --compact
to emit a flat
.I locations
array for editor quickfix/location lists. Compact locations include file, line,
column, line hash, line text, and symbol metadata when available.
.SH INPUTS AND TARGETS
Most commands read a
.I target
path. The
.BR file ,
.BR read ,
.BR map ,
.BR symbol ,
and
.B identify
commands can instead read unsaved buffer text from standard input with
.B --stdin
and
.BR --path .
With
.BR --stdin ,
.B --path
is required, supplies the document name used for language detection, and is
reported in JSON output. A positional target cannot be combined with
.BR --stdin .
.PP
A target may include a line or hash suffix:
.PP
.nf
.RS
\fIfile\fR:\fIline\fR
\fIfile\fR:\fIhash\fR
.RE
.fi
.PP
Line numbers are one-based. Hash suffixes are the 3-character hashes emitted by
.BR read ,
.BR map ,
and
.BR search .
.PP
For
.BR symbol ,
a target may also name a symbol:
.PP
.nf
.RS
\fIfile\fR:\fIsymbol\fR
.RE
.fi
.PP
The symbol can also be supplied as a separate
.I qualified-name
argument. Qualified names and unqualified names are matched against the
structural source map; ambiguous names produce an error.
.PP
For
.BR definition ,
.B --stdin
reads JSON emitted by
.BR identify .
The lookup uses
.I symbol.qualified_name
when present and falls back to
.IR identifier.text .
.SH LANGUAGES
.B readseek
detects languages from file names, extensions, shebangs, and syntax metadata.
Use
.B --language
when detection is ambiguous, when input comes from a synthetic path, or when a
file lacks a useful extension.
.PP
Accepted language identifiers are:
.BR assembly ,
.BR bash ,
.BR c ,
.BR cpp ,
.BR csharp ,
.BR css ,
.BR dockerfile ,
.BR gdscript ,
.BR go ,
.BR html ,
.BR java ,
.BR javascript ,
.BR json ,
.BR jsx ,
.BR just ,
.BR kconfig ,
.BR latex ,
.BR lua ,
.BR make ,
.BR markdown ,
.BR meson ,
.BR nix ,
.BR perl ,
.BR php ,
.BR puppet ,
.BR python ,
.BR riscv ,
.BR ruby ,
.BR rust ,
.BR sql ,
.BR swift ,
.BR toml ,
.BR tsx ,
.BR typescript ,
.BR typst ,
.BR xml ,
.BR yaml ,
and
.BR zig .
The special value
.B unknown
forces text-only handling and disables parser-backed features.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B file
Print detection metadata for the input, including file name, language, parser
support, binary flag, MIME type, and syntax name.
.TP
.B read
Print a line range with line numbers, line hashes, and text. Without a range,
the whole file is returned. A target line or hash,
.BR --start ,
or
.B --offset
sets the first line. Use
.B --end
for an inclusive final line or
.B --limit
for a count.
.TP
.B map
Print the structural source map: symbol kind, name, qualified name, start and end
lines, and boundary hashes. Languages without symbol extraction return an empty
symbol list.
.TP
.B symbol
Print the source range for one symbol. Select it by qualified name, by unqualified
name, by
.IR file:symbol ,
by target line or hash, or by
.BR --line .
.TP
.B identify
Print the requested cursor line, line hash, identifier at the cursor, and the
enclosing mapped symbol. If
.B --column
is omitted, column 1 is used. Columns are one-based byte offsets.
.TP
.B definition
Find mapped symbol definitions in a file or directory. The
.I name
argument matches either a full qualified symbol name or an unqualified name. If
.B --stdin
is used and
.I name
is omitted, the name is selected from an
.B identify
JSON object read from standard input. Directory traversal uses the same file
selection rules as
.BR search .
Use
.B --compact
to emit quickfix-friendly locations instead of the default definition objects.
.TP
.B references
Find whole-identifier references in a file or directory. Output is a flat list
of locations with file, line, column, line hash, line text, and the enclosing
mapped symbol when available. Directory traversal uses the same file selection
rules as
.BR search .
Use
.B --compact
to emit the same locations with symbol metadata flattened into each item.
.TP
.B search
Run an AST pattern against a file or every supported source file below a
directory. Unparseable and unsupported files are skipped. Pattern variables use
.BI $ NAME
for one node and
.BI $$$ NAME
for zero or more sibling nodes.
.PP
Search output is grouped by file and includes the file hash, matched ranges,
captures, boundary hashes, and hashlines for each match.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-h\fR, \fB--help\fR
Display usage information and exit.
.TP
\fB\-V\fR, \fB--version\fR
Print the program version and exit.
.TP
\fB--language\fR \fIlanguage\fR
Override language detection for commands that parse source text. See
.BR LANGUAGES .
.TP
\fB--stdin\fR
Read document contents from standard input instead of opening a target path.
Requires
.BR --path .
For
.BR definition ,
read an
.B identify
JSON object from standard input instead.
.TP
\fB--compact\fR
For
.BR definition
and
.BR references ,
emit
.I locations
with flattened, editor-friendly fields instead of the default command-specific
JSON shape.
.TP
\fB--path\fR \fIpath\fR
Document path to associate with
.BR --stdin .
The path is used for language detection and appears in JSON output.
.TP
\fB--line\fR \fIline\fR
One-based target line for
.B symbol
or
.BR identify .
.TP
\fB--column\fR \fIcolumn\fR
One-based byte column for
.BR identify .
Identifier ranges in JSON use a one-based inclusive start column and a
one-based exclusive end column.
.TP
\fB--start\fR \fIline\fR
First one-based line to include for
.BR read .
.TP
\fB--offset\fR \fIline\fR
Alias for
.BR --start .
.TP
\fB--end\fR \fIline\fR
Last one-based line to include for
.BR read .
Cannot be combined with
.BR --limit .
.TP
\fB--limit\fR \fIn\fR
Maximum number of lines to include for
.BR read .
Cannot be combined with
.BR --end .
.TP
\fB\-c\fR, \fB--cached\fR
When searching a directory inside a Git repository, include tracked/indexed
files.
.TP
\fB\-o\fR, \fB--others\fR
When searching a directory inside a Git repository, include untracked,
non-ignored files.
.TP
\fB\-i\fR, \fB--ignored\fR
With
.BR --others ,
also include ignored untracked files. Inside a Git repository,
.B --ignored
requires
.BR --others .
.SH DIRECTORY SEARCH
The
.BR definition ,
.BR references ,
and
.B search
commands accept either a file or a directory. A file target is searched
directly. A directory target is searched recursively.
.PP
Inside a Git work tree, directory searches use Git-aware selection. With no
selection flags,
.B readseek
searches tracked/indexed files and untracked, non-ignored files. Use
.B --cached
or
.B --others
to restrict the selection. Outside Git work trees, selection flags are ignored
and normal recursive traversal is used.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B READSEEK_CACHE_DIR
Override the base cache directory. When set,
.B readseek
stores the source-map cache below
.IR READSEEK_CACHE_DIR/readseek .
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Operational error, such as a missing file, unsupported binary input, malformed
input, cache error, or symbol lookup failure.
.TP
.B 2
Usage error.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I READSEEK_CACHE_DIR/readseek/cache.sqlite3
Source-map cache when
.B READSEEK_CACHE_DIR
is set.
.TP
.I ${XDG_CACHE_HOME:-~/.cache}/readseek/cache.sqlite3
Typical Linux cache location.
.SH EXAMPLES
Detect a file:
.PP
.EX
readseek file src/main.rs
.EE
.PP
Read lines 10 through 20:
.PP
.EX
readseek read src/main.rs --start 10 --end 20
.EE
.PP
Read 12 lines starting near a target line:
.PP
.EX
readseek read src/main.rs:42 --limit 12
.EE
.PP
Read unsaved buffer text from standard input:
.PP
.EX
printf '%s\\n' 'fn main() {}' | readseek read --stdin --path scratch.rs
.EE
.PP
Build a structural map:
.PP
.EX
readseek map src/main.rs
.EE
.PP
Read a symbol by suffix or by containing line:
.PP
.EX
readseek symbol src/main.rs:run
readseek symbol src/main.rs:270
.EE
.PP
Identify cursor context:
.PP
.EX
readseek identify src/main.rs:42 --column 8
.EE
.PP
Find definitions in tracked files:
.PP
.EX
readseek definition -c src run --language rust
.EE
.PP
Find references in tracked files:
.PP
.EX
readseek references -c src run --language rust
.EE
.PP
Search Rust functions with an AST pattern:
.PP
.EX
readseek search -c src 'fn $NAME() { $$$BODY }' --language rust
.EE
.SH BUILDING
Build from source with:
.PP
.EX
cargo build --release
.EE
.PP
The included Makefile also provides install and uninstall targets.
